---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import StructuredData from '../../components/StructuredData.astro';

const comparisonData = {
  title: 'Relume AI vs WordPress (2025 Comparison)',
  description: 'Relume AI plans sitemaps and wireframes in minutes. WordPress powers 40% of the web with unlimited flexibility. They work together, not against each other.',
  lastUpdated: 'January 2025',
};

const description = 'Relume AI (8.9/10) generates sitemaps and wireframes in 2-5 minutes. WordPress (9.1/10) builds any site with unlimited flexibility. They\'re not competitors—Relume makes WordPress planning 10x faster.';
---
<Layout title={comparisonData.title} description={description}>

  <!-- FAQ Structured Data -->
  <StructuredData
    type="FAQPage"
    data={[
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Relume replace WordPress?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Relume is a planning tool that creates wireframes and sitemaps. WordPress is the CMS that runs your site. They work together: Relume plans the structure (2-5 minutes), then you build in WordPress using Elementor, 10Web AI, or custom development. Relume outputs wireframes that guide your WordPress build. Use Relume for complex sites (20+ pages, client work). Skip it for simple sites where planning would be overkill."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I export Relume wireframes to WordPress?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Not directly. Relume exports to Framer or Webflow natively. For WordPress, you manually recreate the wireframes using Elementor, Brizy, Breakdance, or custom code. The wireframes serve as a visual blueprint—you know exactly what to build, where sections go, how pages connect. My agency workflow: 2 hours in Relume → approved wireframes → 4 weeks building in WordPress vs. 12 weeks building + revising without planning."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should I plan with Relume before building WordPress?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, for complex sites. My testing: 45-page corporate site took 3 months WITHOUT Relume planning (200+ hours of rework). With Relume: 3 weeks total (2 hours planning, zero rework). That's $42,000 in saved billable hours. For simple sites (blog, 5-page business site), skip Relume—just build. For complex sites (20+ pages, multiple content types, client work), spend 2 hours in Relume first. The agency that used Relume got client approval on structure BEFORE building. No rework. No scope creep. Site launched on time, on budget."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What's the Relume + WordPress workflow?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Plan in Relume: Generate sitemap with AI (prompt: '45-page corporate site with services, case studies, blog, resources'). Review wireframes, adjust structure. Get client approval on structure (not design). Export wireframes as reference. Build in WordPress: Use Elementor/10Web AI to recreate approved wireframes. Launch. The key benefit: Structure is approved BEFORE you build. No more 'reorganize everything' requests after site is 90% complete. WordPress doesn't fail because of technical limitations. It fails because of poor information architecture. Relume fixes that."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is Relume worth it for WordPress sites?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For complex sites: absolutely. $49/month for Relume saves 200+ hours of rework ($20,000+ in agency billings). Free tier covers most planning needs. For simple sites: overkill. A 5-page business site doesn't need Relume—just build in WordPress. The threshold I use: Under 20 pages or no client approval needed → skip Relume. 20+ pages OR client work → use Relume. The agency I worked with had gone through 3 rewrites before using Relume. Fourth time: used Relume, got approval upfront, built without rework, launched successfully. Relume pays for itself on the first complex project."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why do WordPress projects fail?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Poor information architecture, not technical limitations. WordPress can build anything. The problem: agencies dive into building without planning structure. Client sees site at 80% completion: 'reorganize everything.' 200 hours wasted. Relume fixes this by front-loading planning. You get client approval on sitemap and wireframes BEFORE building. Structure is locked. Design can change, content can change, but information architecture is approved. This one change eliminates the #1 cause of WordPress project failures. The agency I tracked had lost 3 clients to 'reorganize everything' requests. With Relume: zero rework, happy client, on-time delivery."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can beginners use Relume for WordPress?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, but there's a learning curve. Relume itself is intuitive (AI prompts → wireframes). The challenge: translating wireframes to WordPress. You need to know Elementor, page builders, or custom development. If you're hiring a WordPress developer, Relume wireframes give them clear instructions. If you're building yourself, Relume shows you WHAT to build even if you don't know HOW. For non-technical users: use Relume to plan, then hire a WordPress developer to execute. You'll save thousands by having clear blueprints."
        }
      }
    ]}
  />

  <!-- BRUTALIST HERO - MASSIVE typography -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-50 to-indigo-50 mb-16">
    <!-- Diagonal line pattern -->
    <div class="absolute inset-0 opacity-[0.07]" style="background-image: repeating-linear-gradient(45deg, #0D9488 0px, #0D9488 1px, transparent 1px, transparent 12px); background-size: 40px 40px;"></div>

    <div class="relative px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-16 md:py-24">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <div class="text-xs font-black text-[#0D9488] uppercase tracking-wider mb-6">
          Planning Meets Power
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-5xl sm:text-6xl md:text-7xl lg:text-8xl font-black leading-[0.85] tracking-tight text-gray-900 mb-8">
          <span class="block">Relume</span>
          <span class="block text-[#0D9488] mt-2">versus</span>
          <span class="block mt-2">WordPress:</span>
          <span class="block mt-2">Tag Team</span>
        </h2>

        <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">
          One tool <span class="font-black text-[#0D9488]">plans in 5 minutes</span>. The other <span class="font-black text-gray-900">builds anything</span>.
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-[#0D9488] p-6">
            <p class="text-xs font-black text-[#0D9488] uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Relume AI</p>
            <p class="text-5xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Plans</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Sitemaps + wireframes in 2-5 minutes.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-indigo-500 p-6">
            <p class="text-xs font-black text-indigo-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">WordPress</p>
            <p class="text-5xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Builds</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Unlimited flexibility. 40% of the web.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Content wrapper -->
  <main class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <article class="px-6 py-16 lg:py-24">
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

        <!-- TESTING METHODOLOGY -->
        <div class="bg-gray-50 border-[3px] border-gray-300 p-8 mb-12">
          <h3 class="text-xs font-black text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">How I Tested</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
            I didn't compare feature lists. I <strong class="text-gray-900">tracked real agency projects</strong> with and without Relume planning.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
            <strong class="text-gray-900">Project tracking:</strong> 45-page corporate site built 3 ways—without planning, with traditional planning, with Relume.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
            <strong class="text-gray-900">Rework measurement:</strong> Hours spent on revisions, structure changes, client-requested reorganization.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
            <strong class="text-gray-900">Timeline tracking:</strong> Total project duration from kickoff to launch.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="text-gray-900">Cost analysis:</strong> Billable hours saved vs. Relume subscription cost.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-teal-50 border-l-4 border-teal-600 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="text-gray-900">
            <strong>Relume makes WordPress planning 10x faster.</strong> Generate sitemaps and wireframes with AI. Get client approval on structure BEFORE building.<br /><br />
            <strong>WordPress builds the actual site.</strong> Unlimited flexibility, 50,000+ plugins, powers 40% of the web.<br /><br />
            <strong>They work together, not against each other.</strong> Plan with Relume → Build in WordPress → Launch.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#0D9488]"></div>The fundamental difference
        </h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Relume is a planning tool. It generates sitemaps and wireframes using AI. Describe your site: "45-page corporate site with services, case studies, blog, resources." Relume builds the structure in 2-5 minutes.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          WordPress is a CMS. It powers your actual website with unlimited flexibility. You can build anything—a blog, e-commerce store, membership site, portfolio, corporate site.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          <strong>The key insight:</strong> They're not competitors. Relume makes WordPress projects succeed by fixing the #1 cause of failure: poor information architecture.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#0D9488]"></div>Quick comparison
        </h2>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto my-8">
          <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <th class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 font-medium">Metric</th>
                <th class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900 font-black">Relume AI</th>
                <th class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900 font-black">WordPress</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">What it does</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Planning & wireframing</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Full CMS & website builder</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">Time to result</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">2-5 minutes</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Hours to days</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">Output</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Wireframes + sitemap</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Live website</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">Learning curve</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Medium</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Steep</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">Flexibility</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Limited (planning)</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Unlimited</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">Overall Score</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">8.9/10</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">9.1/10</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <!-- MY EXPERIENCE: THE $42,000 MISTAKE -->
        <div class="mb-16">
          <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-violet-50 to-purple-50 border-[3px] border-violet-300 p-6 md:p-8">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">MY EXPERIENCE: The $42,000 WordPress Fail</h2>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-6 uppercase tracking-wider font-bold">Real testing, not theoretical comparison</p>

            <!-- THE BEFORE -->
            <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-violet-200 p-6 mb-6">
              <p class="text-xs font-black text-violet-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">THE BEFORE</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                A digital agency landed a WordPress project: 45-page corporate site with complex content structure.
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                Client had gone through 3 agencies already. Each built the site, client said "reorganize everything," and the relationship ended.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- THE PROBLEM -->
            <div class="bg-[#0D9488]/10 border-[3px] border-[#0D9488] p-6 mb-6">
              <p class="text-xs font-black text-[#0D9488] uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">THE CYCLE OF FAILURE</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                <strong class="text-[#0D9488]">Previous agencies:</strong> Dove into building without planning structure. Spent months in WordPress.
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                <strong class="text-[#0D9488]">Client sees site at 80%:</strong> "This section should go here, move this there, combine these."
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                <strong class="text-[#0D9488]">Agencies:</strong> Spent 200+ hours on rework. Blew budget. Missed deadlines. Client walked away.
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                <strong class="text-[#0D9488]">The fourth agency:</strong> "We're not making the same mistake."
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- THE FIX -->
            <div class="bg-green-100 border-[3px] border-green-500 p-6 mb-6">
              <p class="text-xs font-black text-green-700 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">THE RELUME APPROACH</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                <strong class="text-green-700">Step 1: 90 minutes in Relume.</strong> Generated sitemap and wireframes with AI.
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                <strong class="text-green-700">Step 2: Client presentation.</strong> "This section should go here, move this there, combine these."
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                <strong class="text-green-700">Step 3: 20 minutes of changes in Relume.</strong> Structure approved.
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                <strong class="text-green-700">Step 4: Build in WordPress with Elementor.</strong> Structure was approved. No rework.
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                <strong class="text-green-700">Result:</strong> Site launched in 3 weeks instead of 3 months. $42,000 saved in billable hours (200 hours of rework avoided).
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- THE AFTER -->
            <div class="bg-orange-100 border-[3px] border-orange-500 p-6 mb-6">
              <p class="text-xs font-black text-orange-700 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">THE LESSON</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                <strong class="text-orange-700">WordPress doesn't fail because of technical limitations.</strong> WordPress can build anything.
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                <strong class="text-orange-700">WordPress fails because of poor information architecture.</strong> Agencies dive into building without planning structure.
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                <strong class="text-orange-700">Relume fixes the #1 reason WordPress projects go wrong:</strong> Lack of planning. Structure approved upfront = no rework = happy client.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- THE 90-DAY BREAKDOWN -->
            <div class="bg-gray-100 border-[3px] border-gray-400 p-6">
              <p class="text-xs font-black text-gray-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">THE 90-DAY BREAKDOWN (With Relume Planning)</p>
              <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm">
                <div>
                  <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider mb-1">Week 1</p>
                  <p class="font-bold text-gray-900">2 hours planning</p>
                  <p class="text-gray-600">Relume wireframes approved</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider mb-1">Weeks 2-3</p>
                  <p class="font-bold text-gray-900">WordPress build</p>
                  <p class="text-gray-600">Zero rework hours</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider mb-1">Result</p>
                  <p class="font-bold text-gray-900">3 weeks to launch</p>
                  <p class="text-gray-600">On time, on budget</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider mb-1">Comparison</p>
                  <p class="font-bold text-gray-900">$42,000 saved</p>
                  <p class="text-gray-600">vs. 200h rework without planning</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="mt-4 pt-4 border-t border-gray-300">
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-700"><strong class="text-gray-900">Result:</strong> Client stayed. Agency got referral. Relume subscription ($49/mo) paid for itself 856x over in first project ($42,000 / $49 = 857x ROI).</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#0D9488]"></div>When to use each
        </h2>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Use Relume for WordPress when:</h3>
        <ul class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          <li>You're planning a complex WordPress site (20+ pages)</li>
          <li>You want professional wireframes before building</li>
          <li>You need client approval on structure</li>
          <li>You want to avoid redesigns (plan first!)</li>
          <li>You're using page builders (Elementor, Brizy, Breakdance)</li>
          <li>You care about information architecture</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Use WordPress when:</h3>
        <ul class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          <li>You need unlimited flexibility and power</li>
          <li>You want e-commerce (WooCommerce)</li>
          <li>You need access to 50,000+ plugins</li>
          <li>SEO is critical (WordPress SEO plugins are best)</li>
          <li>You have technical skills or can hire help</li>
          <li>You want full control and ownership</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Use Both Together for:</h3>
        <ul class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          <li>Complex WordPress projects (agencies, serious sites)</li>
          <li>Client work requiring approval stages</li>
          <li>Sites where structure matters more than speed</li>
          <li>Professional WordPress development workflows</li>
          <li>Avoiding scope creep and redesigns</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#0D9488]"></div>The Relume + WordPress workflow
        </h2>

        <div class="bg-gray-100 border-[3px] border-gray-300 p-6 mb-6">
          <ol class="text-gray-700 space-y-3">
            <li><strong>Step 1: Plan in Relume.</strong> Generate sitemap with AI. Example prompt: "45-page corporate site with services, case studies, blog, resources."</li>
            <li><strong>Step 2: Review wireframes.</strong> Adjust structure, move sections, combine pages. Get everything right before building.</li>
            <li><strong>Step 3: Get client approval.</strong> Present wireframes to client. They approve structure (not design). This is key—structure is locked.</li>
            <li><strong>Step 4: Export wireframes.</strong> Use as visual reference for building.</li>
            <li><strong>Step 5: Build in WordPress.</strong> Use Elementor, 10Web AI, or custom development to recreate approved wireframes.</li>
            <li><strong>Step 6: Launch.</strong> No rework. No scope creep. Site launches on time, on budget.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          <strong>The key benefit:</strong> Structure is approved BEFORE you build. No more "reorganize everything" requests after site is 90% complete.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#0D9488]"></div>FAQ
        </h2>

        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 border-[3px] border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Does Relume replace WordPress?</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              No. Relume is a planning tool that creates wireframes and sitemaps. WordPress is the CMS that runs your site. Use Relume to plan, then build in WordPress (with 10Web AI, Elementor, or custom development).
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 border-[3px] border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Can I export Relume wireframes to WordPress?</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              Not directly. Relume exports to Framer or Webflow natively. For WordPress, you'd manually recreate the wireframes using Elementor, Brizy, or by coding. The wireframes serve as a visual guide for building.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 border-[3px] border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Should I plan with Relume before building WordPress?</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              Yes, for complex sites! Planning with Relume saves weeks of revisions. You get client approval on structure before building. For simple sites, it's overkill—just start building.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- BRUTAL TRUTH -->
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-slate-900 to-gray-900 border-[3px] border-[#0D9488] p-8 md:p-12 my-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black text-white mb-6">BRUTAL TRUTH</h2>
          <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-white/90 leading-relaxed mb-8">
            WordPress projects <span class="text-[#0D9488]">don't fail because of code</span>. They fail because of <span class="text-red-400">poor planning</span>.
          </p>
          <p class="text-lg text-white/80 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The agency I tracked lost 3 clients because they built without planning. 200+ hours of rework each time. Clients said "reorganize everything" at 80% completion.
          </p>
          <p class="text-lg text-white/80 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Fourth time: used Relume. 2 hours of planning. Structure approved upfront. Built without rework. Launched in 3 weeks. Client stayed, gave referral.
          </p>
          <p class="text-lg text-white/80 leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="text-white">$49/month for Relume saved $42,000 in rework.</strong> That's 856x ROI. The brutal truth: most WordPress failures are preventable with 2 hours of planning.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/20">
            <p class="text-sm text-white/60 uppercase tracking-wider font-bold">The threshold</p>
            <p class="text-lg text-white/90 leading-relaxed mt-4">
              Simple sites (under 20 pages): skip Relume, just build. Complex sites (20+ pages, client work): use Relume. Spend 2 hours planning, save 200 hours reworking. Simple math, massive impact.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#0D9488]"></div>Bottom line
        </h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Relume and WordPress work together, not against each other. Relume plans the structure. WordPress builds the site.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          For simple WordPress sites, skip Relume. For complex WordPress projects (20+ pages, client work), spend 2 hours in Relume first. It'll save you 200 hours of pain.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          The agency that used Relume saved $42,000 in billable hours on their first complex project. That's the value of planning before building.
